Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
createSignalPin(25.10)                                  createSignalPin(25.10)

Name
       createSignalPin  - Promotes signal pins in the IO pad/block to the top-
       level design as a physical pin for specified instances or pins

Syntax
       createSignalPin

       [-help]

       [-ignore_floating_pins]

       {-inst <inst_name_list> | -pins <pin_name_list>}

       Promotes signal pins in the IO pad/block to the top-level design  as  a
       physical  pin for specified instances or pins. The instance's cell type
       should be either CLASS PAD AREAIO or CLASS BLOCK. The pins to  be  pro-
       moted  should  have geometry on the top layer. You can choose to ignore
       floating pins.

Parameters
       -help  Prints a brief description that includes type and default infor-
              mation for each createSignalPin parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man createSignalPin

       -ignore_floating_pins
              Ignores the floating pins. If this parameter  is  not  specified
              when  promoting  pins  to  the  top level, the tool converts the
              floating pins in the instance to pgTerms because these pins  are
              not logically connected to any terminal on the top level.

       -inst <inst_name_list>
              Specifies  the names of instances for which pins need to be cre-
              ated.

              Note: This option cannot be used with -pins.

       -pins <pin_name_list>
              Lists specific pins that are to be promoted to  the  top  level.
              The specified pins should be hierarchical.

              Note: This option cannot be used with -inst.

Examples
              * The instance lna_inst has a signal pin called data1_i. The pin
                data1_i  has  a  port geometry shape on the top layer. The lef
                for the lna cell is as follows:

                MACRO lna

                CLASS BLOCK ;

                ......

                  PIN data1_i

                    DIRECTION INPUT ;

                    USE SIGNAL ;

                    PORT

                        CLASS BUMP ;

                        LAYER METAL8 ;

                        RECT   10.00 10.00   20.00 100.00 ;

                    END

                  END data1_i

                ....

                END lna

                The following command creates a signal pin  for  the  instance
                lna_inst:

                createSignalPin -inst lna_inst

                *

                  Before this command is run, the pin is local to lna_inst:

                * After the command is run, the pin is promoted:

              * The  following  command promotes the specified pins to the top
                level:

                createSignalPin   -pins   {lna_inst/data1_i   lna_inst/data2_i
                phy/QS_PADP}

